  "10": {
    "John H. Walton, John K. Riches": "). The Lord then delivers a prophetic\nrevelation to Samuel (vv. 11\u201314). Through its structure and\nprogression the story draws attention to the shift in authority in\nSamuel\u2019s life. Initially he goes to Eli, but then, as instructed by Eli,\nhe speaks to the Lord, calling himself the Lord\u2019s servant. As Samuel\ndelivers the prophetic message to Eli, one senses that their\nrelationship will never be the same. Now Samuel is the Lord\u2019s\nspokesman, whose prophetic word has authority even over Eli. By\nthe end of the chapter, \u201call Israel from Dan to Beersheba\u201d (\nv. 10),\nwhich David `[char_David_Rut_4]` himself recognizes (\n10. Gire, Windows to the Soul, 111\u201313.\n[v_2Sa_18_1] 2 Samuel 18:1\u201319:8",
    "John Trapp": "And reigned two years, ] sc., Peaceably and quietly, before war fell out betwixt him and David `[char_David_Rut_4]`. So Saul is said to have reigned two years, { #1Sa 13:1 } that is, free from foreign enemies, and unmolested by the Philistines. After this, there was five years\u2019 war betwixt the house of Saul and the house of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, till Ishbosheth\u2019s death. { #2Sa 3:1 } But the house of Judah followed David `[char_David_Rut_4]`. ] Yet were they not guilty of the sin of schism: no more are the Reformed Churches, for forsaking of Antichrist, to follow the Lamb wheresoever he goeth, to set the crown upon the Lord Christ\u2019s head.\nVer.\n10. And reigned two years, ] sc., Peaceably and quietly, before war fell out betwixt him and David `[char_David_Rut_4]`. So Saul is said to have reigned two years, {#1Sa 13:1} that is, free from foreign enemies, and unmolested by the Philistines. After this, there was five years\u2019 war betwixt the house of Saul and the house of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, till Ishbosheth\u2019s death. {#2Sa 3:1} But the house of Judah followed David `[char_David_Rut_4]`.] Yet were they not guilty of the sin of schism: no more are the Reformed Churches, for forsaking of Antichrist, to follow the Lamb wheresoever he goeth, to set the crown upon the Lord Christ\u2019s head.\nVer."
  },
  "20": {
    "John H. Walton, John K. Riches": ")\nrecognizes Samuel, not Eli, as the Lord\u2019s chosen servant through\nwhom he\nKey Themes of 1 Samuel 3 reveals his word to Israel. From this time\nforward, Samuel, not Eli, will lead Israel. The text makes it clear\nthat Samuel does not represent a minority faction bent on imposing\nits will on the nation.\n3:2 he could barely see\ufffd Eli\u2019s blindness mirrors the situation in\nIsrael under his and his sons\u2019 leadership; prophetic visions are rare\n(\nv. 20) and receives his prophetic word (4:1a). (4) The\nLord continues to reveal himself to Samuel at Shiloh (\n20. This is yet another link binding Samuel, the Lord\u2019s chosen prophet,\nto David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, whom Samuel will anoint as the Lord\u2019s chosen king and\nwith whom the Lord will make a binding covenant.\nAs noted above, this chapter complements the previous one and\nfurther develops the theme stated in 2:30: The Lord honors those\nwho honor him but rejects those who despise him. The Lord\u2019s\nrejection of Eli\u2019s house is reiterated in 3:11\u201314, but the focus of",
    "John Trapp": "Art thou Asahel? ] Abner had no mind to meddle with any son of Zeruiah, David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s sister: he therefore first turneth querist to this currist, -Luther\u2019s words, -and then twice adviseth him to retreat from pursuing his own peril. But quisque suos patitur manes.\nVer.\n20. Ver.\n20. Art thou Asahel?] Abner had no mind to meddle with any son of Zeruiah, David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s sister: he therefore first turneth querist to this currist, -Luther\u2019s words, -and then twice adviseth him to retreat from pursuing his own peril. But quisque suos patitur manes.\nVer.\n20. Ver.",
    "930072315325": "And David `[char_David_Rut_4]` came to Baalperazim, etc.] As it was after called, for\nhere it has its name by anticipation, and whither the Philistines were come\n[v_1Ch_14_11] from the valley of Rephaim; (see <131411>1 Chronicles 14:11); which was at no\ngreat distance, the one being the hill, to which the other was the valley,\ncomputed to be about three miles from Jerusalem, in the way to Bethlehem\nf97, between which places were two hours\u2019 travels f98:\nand David `[char_David_Rut_4]` smote them there; there a battle was fought, in which David `[char_David_Rut_4]` had\nthe victory assured him:\nand said, the Lord hath broken forth upon mine enemies before me, as the\nbreach of waters; as when waters, through their mighty force, break down\nthe banks of rivers, and carry all before them; or as one breaks an earthen\n[v_1Ch_14_11] vessel full of water, so the Targum on (<131411>1 Chronicles 14:11).\ntherefore he called the name of the place Baalperazim; which signifies\n\u201cthe master of breaches\u201d, where the Philistines were broke in upon, and\nbroken to pieces, of which God was the author, and which gave David `[char_David_Rut_4]` the\nmastery over his enemies; the Targum renders it \u201cthe plain of breaches\u201d,\nand seems to take it to be the same with the valley of Rephaim; (see <100522>2\nSamuel 5:22).\nVer."
  },
