    "John H. Walton, John K. Riches": ").2 The ark is kept in the inner sanctuary, at the\nrear of the tabernacle proper, while Samuel is sleeping in the nave,\nor main area.3 There is a contrast between Samuel, who is \u201clying\ndown\u201d in his usual place near God\u2019s presence (vv. 2\u20133), and Eli\u2019s\nsons, who \u201cslept\u201d with the women serving at the tent of meeting\n3. See Anderson, 2 Samuel, 84.\n3. McCarter (ibid., 243) suggests a slight alteration of 2 Sam. 8:3\nMT (from lehashib, \u201cto return,\u201d to lehoshib, \u201cto place\u201d) and translates\n\u201cto leave his stela.\u201d\n3. Sternberg, The Poetics of Biblical Narrative, 214.\n3. Fokkelman, Narrative Art and Poetry, 104.\n3. For further discussion of the narrator\u2019s characterization of\nAbsalom here, see Fokkelman, Narrative Art and Poetry, 151.\n3. McCarter, II Samuel, 377; Fokkelman, Narrative Art\nand Poetry, 191; Bergen, 1, 2 Samuel, 406.\n3. Olsen, \u201cCash\u2019s Song,\u201d http://www.christianitytoday",
    "Tony W. Cartledge": "Absalom returns to the palace (14:25-33)\nC. Absalom\u2019s Rebellion (15:1\u201318:33)\n3. Parting shots from Saul\u2019s house (16:1-14)\n3. David `[char_David_Rut_4]` reaffirmed by Israel (19:41-43)\nB. David `[char_David_Rut_4]` deals with internal dissent (20:1-26)\n3. Sheba\u2019s end: the wise woman of Abel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]` (20:14-22)",
    "John Trapp": "And his men that were with him did David `[char_David_Rut_4]` bring up. ] Those that came to him, { #1Sa 22:2 } and continued with him in all his troubles. He cashiereth them not for all their recent rebellion at Ziklag, which was yet fresh, and but a few days since: but pardoning their rebellions, he maketh them partakers of his good success. Thus doth our heavenly Leader, whom David `[char_David_Rut_4]` prefigured, take us to reign with him, who have suffered with him. And they dwelt in the cities of Hebron. ] They were billeted up and down in the neighbouring towns and villages, called daughters, { #Jos 21:11,12 } lest he should be burdensome to his Hebronites, by quartering upon them sa great a company.\nVer.\n3. And his men that were with him did David `[char_David_Rut_4]` bring up.] Those that came to him, {#1Sa 22:2} and continued with him in all his troubles. He cashiereth them not for all their recent rebellion at Ziklag, which was yet fresh, and but a few days since: but pardoning their rebellions, he maketh them partakers of his good success. Thus doth our heavenly Leader, whom David `[char_David_Rut_4]` prefigured, take us to reign with him, who have suffered with him. And they dwelt in the cities of Hebron.] They were billeted up and down in the neighbouring towns and villages, called daughters, [v_Jos_21_11] {#Jos 21:11,12} lest he should be burdensome to his Hebronites, by quartering upon them sa great a company.\nVer.",
